        heading: "Conventional vs Synthetic vs Synthetic Blend",
        content:
          "Conventional oil is refined directly from crude oil and works fine for older vehicles and short oil change intervals. It costs less per quart but needs to be changed more frequently — typically every 3,000 to 5,000 miles. Synthetic oil is engineered at the molecular level to provide superior protection, flow better at extreme temperatures, resist breakdown longer, and keep engines cleaner. Full synthetic oil can go 7,500 to 10,000 miles between changes, and some manufacturers like BMW and Mercedes require it. Synthetic blend is a mix of conventional and synthetic base oils that provides some of the benefits of synthetic at a lower price point, with a typical change interval of 5,000 to 7,500 miles. For Cleveland drivers, synthetic oil has a specific advantage beyond longevity: cold-weather flow. When you start your car on a 10-degree January morning, the first 30 to 60 seconds of engine operation cause the most wear because the oil has thickened overnight and has not yet reached all the bearing surfaces. Synthetic oil flows significantly faster in cold temperatures than conventional oil, reducing cold-start wear. Over 100,000 miles of Cleveland winters, that cold-flow advantage translates into meaningfully less engine wear. If your vehicle does not require synthetic oil but you want the best protection for Cleveland conditions, we recommend at minimum a synthetic blend. The $20 to $30 price difference per oil change pays for itself in extended engine life.",
